Mix the @Ras-el-Hanout{1} with @olive oil{1%tsp}. Rub the mixture over the
@salmon fillet{2} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of
@black pepper{pinch}. Leave to rest until we've done a bit more of the prep.

Peel and finely chop the @red onion{1/2}. Finely chop the @mint leaves{3}. Finely
chop the @vine tomatoes{2} into cubes (½cm small if your knife skills allow!).

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Add the red onion
with a good pinch of salt and pepper. Slowly cook with a #lid{} on the pan for
~{20%minutes} until soft and sweet.

> Tip: Check back to make sure they are not sticking to the pan and add a dash
> of water if they are.

Once the red onion is cooked add @water{250%ml} to the pan. Once it comes to a
boil add half the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} and remove the pan from the heat.
Add the @couscous{3/4%Couscous} into the pan and stir everything together. Place
a lid on the pan for ~{5%minutes} whilst you cook the fish.

Pre-heat your #grill{} to high. Heat @olive oil{1%tsp} in a #non-stick frying pan{}
on medium heat. Get your pan nice and hot before placing the salmon in the pan,
skin-side down. Cook for ~{4%minutes} without touching the salmon.

Take your salmon off the hob and place it on the top shelf under your grill.
Leave it for ~{4%minutes}, or until cooked to your liking. Remove from under the
grill and add @?butter{2%tsp}(if you have some and feel decadent!). Squeeze
@lemon juice{2%tsp} and spoon over your salmon.

Stir the chopped mint and tomato into the couscous. Pour any juices from the pan
into the couscous and stir. Grate in @lemon zest{1/4%tsp} (more if you want it
really citrussy).

To serve, place your couscous into your #bowl{}, top it off with your salmon and
squeeze over a little more @lemon{1/2}(juiced) juice.